  "original_title": "\u0d91\u0d9a\u0dca\u0dc3\u0dad\u0dca \u0da2\u0dcf\u0dad\u0dd3\u0db1\u0dca\u0d9c\u0dda \u0dc3\u0dcf\u0d9c\u0dbb \u0dc3\u0db8\u0dd4\u0dc5\u0dd4\u0dc0 \u0dc3\u0dcf\u0dbb\u0dca\u0dae\u0d9a\u0dc0 \u0db4\u0dd0\u0dc0\u0dad\u0dca\u0dc0\u0dda",
  "text_idx": {
    "en": {
      "title": "The UN Ocean Conference is successfully held",
      "author": "unknown",
      "body_lines": [
        "The United Nations Ocean Summit began on June 27, where states around the world are stepping up their leadership in combating plastic pollution.",
        "The global commitment, established in 2018 and led by the Ellen MacArthur Foundation in collaboration with the United Nations Environment Program (UNEP), has gathered more than 500 signatures, including businesses, governments and other organizations, to transition to an alternative economy for plastics.",
        "The United Nations Ocean Conference was held in Lisbon, Portugal from June 27 to July 1.",
        "Plastic is everywhere in our lives, but after we use it, it ends up in the ocean. According to the United Nations, at least 11 million tons of plastic waste enter the ocean every year, which is 80% of all marine debris.",
        "Plastic pollution can have a serious impact on the entire marine ecosystem. Plastic gets entangled in the bodies of animals and is eaten by marine species. According to the United Nations, more than 800 marine and coastal animal species are affected by this pollution. Plastic waste kills 1 million seabirds, 100,000 marine mammals, sea turtles and countless fish every year."
      ],
